{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775847251930,"sessionID":"ses_28741be16ffex4k31WreDJMoNA","part":{"id":"prt_d78be9fb7001z7BpuA1ZCInJNB","messageID":"msg_d78be4d270013N1HKIcOBUgrzK","sessionID":"ses_28741be16ffex4k31WreDJMoNA","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-e5251a62d0d342dcab0ba2e57f95cbc4","state":{"status":"error","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-008 - Sandbox GC 定时清理机制\n\n## Overview\n\n**Action Request:** AR-008 — Sandbox GC 定时清理机制  \n**Module:** `pkg/workloadmanager`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** S  \n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement a scheduled garbage collection (GC) mechanism for sandbox resources in the AgentCube workload manager. This mechanism will:\n\n- Periodically identify and clean up orphaned or expired sandbox resources\n- Prevent resource leaks and optimize cluster resource utilization\n- Ensure timely cleanup of sandboxes that are no longer in use or have exceeded their lifecycle\n\nThe GC mechanism will operate on both `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` resources, aligning with the runtime API group (`runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`).\n\n## Scope\n\n### Core Functionality\n\n1. **Scheduled Cleanup Cycle**\n   - Implement a configurable timer-based cleanup routine\n   - Support configurable cleanup intervals (default: 1 hour)\n   - Allow per-resource-type cleanup frequency tuning\n\n2. **Resource Identification**\n   - Query `AgentRuntime` resources with expired/invalid states\n   - Query `CodeInterpreter` resources with expired/invalid states\n   - Identify resources lacking associated workload/Pod references\n\n3. **Cleanup Actions**\n   - Delete identified resources via Kubernetes client API\n   - Log cleanup actions with detailed metrics\n   - Emit events on successful and failed cleanup operations\n\n4. **Metrics and Observability**\n   - Track GC cycle counts and duration\n   - Monitor resources cleaned per cycle\n   - Expose Prometheus metrics for monitoring\n\n### Implementation Components\n\n- **Location:** `pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox_gc.go`\n- **Dependencies:** \n  - `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` (for typed clients)\n  - `k8s.io/client-go` (for standard Kubernetes clients)\n  - `k8s.io/apimachinery` (for API types)\n\n### Integration Points\n\n- Leverage existing `SharedInformerFactory` for efficient cache access\n- Integrate with workload manager lifecycle (start/stop GC routine)\n- Respect namespace-scoped operations where applicable\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Positive Impacts\n\n1. **Resource Efficiency**\n   - Prevents accumulation of orphaned sandbox resources\n   - Reduces unnecessary etcd storage usage\n   - Frees up compute/network resources for active workloads\n\n2. **Operational Stability**\n   - Mitigates resource exhaustion scenarios\n   - Improves overall cluster health and performance\n   - Reduces manual cleanup overhead for operators\n\n3. **Consistency**\n   - Ensures predictable cleanup behavior across deployments\n   - Maintains alignment with Kubernetes garbage collection patterns\n\n### Potential Risks\n\n1. **Aggressive Cleanup**\n   - Risk: Deleting resources still in transient states\n   - Mitigation: Implement robust state validation and grace periods\n\n2. **Performance Impact**\n   - Risk: Periodic list operations may load API server during large-scale deployments\n   - Mitigation: Use informer caches, batch operations, and configurable intervals\n\n3. **Race Conditions**\n   - Risk: Concurrent creation/deletion conflicts\n   - Mitigation: Implement optimistic concurrency control with resource versioning\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Operator-Driven Manual Cleanup\n- **Description:** Rely on human operators or external scripts to identify and clean up resources\n- **Pros:** Full operator control, minimal controller complexity\n- **Cons:** High operational overhead, inconsistent timing, error-prone\n- **Decision:** Rejected - automation is preferred for reliability\n\n### Alternative 2: Kubernetes Built-in Owner References\n- **Description:** Leverage Kubernetes' native garbage collection via ownerReferences\n- **Pros:** Native Kubernetes mechanism, no custom logic required\n- **Cons:** Limited to parent-child relationships, cannot handle complex lifecycle scenarios (e.g., time-based expiry)\n- **Decision:** Partial - use ownerReferences where applicable, but still need custom GC for advanced cleanup policies\n\n### Alternative 3: Event-Driven Cleanup\n- **Description:** Trigger cleanup actions based on Pod/workload state change events\n- **Pros:** Immediate response to state changes\n- **Cons:** Higher complexity, potential for event storms, may miss orphaned resources\n- **Decision:** Rejected - periodic GC provides more predictable and comprehensive coverage\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Core GC Engine (Week 1-2)\n- Implement `SandboxGC` struct and basic timer loop\n- Add client initialization for `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter`\n- Implement resource list and state validation logic\n\n### Phase 2: Cleanup Logic (Week 3)\n- Add deletion operations with proper error handling\n- Implement grace period and state validation rules\n- Add comprehensive logging and metrics\n\n### Phase 3: Configuration and Testing (Week 4)\n- Expose configuration options (interval, grace period, dry-run mode)\n- Write unit tests and integration tests\n- Document configuration and behavior\n\n### Phase 4: Integration and Monitoring (Week 5)\n- Integrate with workload manager startup/shutdown lifecycle\n- Add Prometheus metrics endpoint\n- Perform end-to-end testing and performance validation\n\n## Configuration\n\nThe GC mechanism will support the following configuration parameters:\n\n| Parameter | Default | Description |\n|-----------|---------|-------------|\n| `gc.interval` | 1h | Frequency of cleanup cycles |\n| `gc.agentRuntime.gracePeriod` | 24h | Time before deleting expired AgentRuntimes |\n| `gc.codeInterpreter.gracePeriod` | 12h | Time before deleting expired CodeInterpreters |\n| `gc.dryRun` | false | When true, log resources without deleting |\n| `gc.metrics.enabled` | true | Enable Prometheus metrics export |\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n1. **Unit Tests**\n   - Test resource identification logic\n   - Validate state detection rules\n   - Mock Kubernetes client for isolated testing\n\n2. **Integration Tests**\n   - Test with fake clientset\n   - Verify cleanup actions in simulated environment\n   - Test error handling and recovery\n\n3. **E2E Tests**\n   - Deploy test workload with known lifecycle\n   - Verify GC cleanup behavior\n   - Validate metrics and observability\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- GC cycle runs successfully at configured intervals\n- Orphaned resources are identified and cleaned up within grace period\n- No false positives (active resources are never deleted)\n- Metrics accurately reflect GC operations\n- System performance impact is negligible (< 1% CPU overhead during GC cycle)\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- Kubernetes client-go library\n- AgentCube client-go (already generated)\n- Prometheus client library (for metrics)\n- Standard Go libraries (time, context, logging)\n\n## Rollout Plan\n\n1. Deploy with `dryRun=true` initially to validate behavior\n2. Monitor logs and metrics for accuracy\n3. Enable actual cleanup operations after validation period (1 week)\n4. Gradually adjust interval and grace period based on cluster characteristics\n\n## References\n\n- `deployment/client-go.md` - Generated Kubernetes client for AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources\n- Kubernetes Garbage Collection documentation\n- Volcano workload management patterns","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775847251921,"end":1775847251926}}}}
